\begin_layout Subsection*
Why the Analytical Hierarchy Process (AHP)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AHP provides an axiomatic framework (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saaty1986"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

...logic and reasoning with the aid of very small samples of data
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ehrig2026"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 It is a multi-criterion decision methodology (MCDM) enjoying widespread applicability for group decision making (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saaty1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

),
 risk analysis (e.g.,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saaty1987,Vaidya2006,Linkov2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

),
 and other problems.
 AHP is often applied to situations where substantial amounts of statistically coherent measurements are not immediately available to support more-empirical approaches.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The AHP methodology begins with identifying a plausible 
\emph on
evidentiary span
\emph default
:
 The range of measurable factors believed to influence the attractiveness of each distinct scenario under consideration.
 The responsible individual decision maker or panel of experts then performs
\emph on
 pairwise comparisons
\emph default
 to assign a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preference ratio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between each pair of factors within the range (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Merrick2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Illustrated in a case study in a subsequent section,
 AHP produces the scenario rankings according to attractiveness based upon their respective measurable factors.
 Bayesian methods (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Li2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) allow for subsequent revision of the pairwise comparisons as stronger empirical evidence emerges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Evidentiary-strength analysis using the AHP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That 
\emph on
a set of AHP pairwise comparisons defines a complete,
 directed,
 acyclic graph
\emph default
 (DAG) provides the seminal insight underlying this investigation.
 Complete DAGs belong to a special class of graphs called 
\emph on
tournament graphs
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Moon2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In general,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the entropy of a graph is interpreted 
\emph on
as its structural information content
\emph default
 and serves as a complexity measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (emphasis added) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dehmer2011,Mowshowitz2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brown2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studied the particular characteristics of tournament graphs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
What questions do entropies of AHP-based tournament graphs allow us to answer
\emph default
?
 Endogenous to the AHP formulation itself,
 relative entropy quantifies the marginal informational contribution by a subset of factors within the evidentiary span.
 This addresses a the objective pursued by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hué2026"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Graph-entropy measures however do not require extensive data comprised of both positive and negative cases as with Hué's approach.
 Congruent with the AHP methodology explored here,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 use entropy of
\emph on
 belief-function graphical models
\emph default
 to decompose their relative evidentiary strength.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
By what mechanism do we infer the differential information between AHP-based tournament graphs with distinct evidentiary spans
\emph default
?
 Relative entropy provides a well-understood approach (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cover2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Relative entropy for graphs has received considerable attention (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wong1985,Liu2022,Guanlei2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brown2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explore entropy differences between same-order tournament graphs with different directional structures.
 In our case,
 the relative entropy of the graph associated with the overall evidentiary span with respect to a constituent induced subgraph quantifies the information lost due to decision factors omitted from the latter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
What innovation is required to define a methodology for AHP-based evidentiary-strength analysis
\emph default
?
 First,
 we must formulate an entropy definition for tournament graphs with 
\emph on
weighted
\emph default
 edges.
 The investigation by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brown2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 focused on tournament graphs with unweighted (uniformly unit-weighted) edges.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chen2015,Kuo2022,Liu2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 formulate entropies for regular (non-directional) graphs comprised of weighted edges.
 The preference ratios from the AHP pairwise comparison provide the weights used here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 relative entropies of hierarchically linked AHP subgraphs must be coupled.
 The 
\emph on
Hierarchy
\emph default
 term in AHP refers to a hierarchic deconstruction of decisions into contituent factors.
 The AHP method produces a set of decision-factor pairwise comparisons —
 and associated tournament graph —
 for each hierarchic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cluster
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "§2.5"
key "Cover2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe 
\emph on
chain rules
\emph default
 for entropy,
 relative entropy,
 and mutual information.
 Such mechanisms offer a rigorous approach to link hierarchically adjacent tournament graphs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Why is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

heavy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 graph-entropy machinery needed
\emph default
?
 We might intiutively expect that individual pairwise preference ratios suffice to inform us about the most-influential factors.
 The AHP's machinery however accounts for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mutual coupling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between decision factors (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saaty1986"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 That pairwise comparisons define a graph —
 a network —
 provides the basis of its power.
 Our graph-entropy machinery accounts for the 
\emph on
aggegate effect
\emph default
 of all the evidence informing a decision or risk assessment.
 Individual preference ratios fail to provide this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Course of investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with a brief illustration of AHP methodology.
 A 
\emph on
real-world
\emph default
 case study concisely demonstrates its application to obtaining a preference-ranked set of scenarios.
 The actual ranking lies beyond our specific interest.
 The DAGs resulting from the pairwise preferences provide our focus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then calculate the entropy for our pairwise-preference DAG.
 This extends work by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brown2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 through construction of a Laplacian that includes the edge weights.
 Our AHP-graph Laplacian fuses elements of that for a conventional unit-edge-weighted DAG Laplacian with components from the AHP reciprocal matrix for edge weights.
 This incorporates information about degree of influence in the interconnected evidentiary framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then calculate entropies and relative entropies from our AHP-based DAG structure and interpret the results for our real-world case study.
 Approaches demonstrated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiroušek2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 guide our thinking.
 We also explore the relationship between preference ratios relative entroy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Case study in the Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bu2026"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 applied AHP methodology in design-tradeoff decisions for hydrogen fuel cells.
 Their work involves deep consideration of device physics that are tangential to the present exploration.
 Their use of the AHP methodology primarily interests us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This case study suits the purposes of this investigation for three reasons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
It demonstrates a real-world application
\emph default
.
 Introductory AHP presentations often employ contrived cases.
 A real-world case study provides a more-informative and -convincing demonstration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
This case is recent
\emph default
.
 Given the AHP literature spans decades,
 a reader might succomb to the temptation to conclude that the method is anochronistic.
 Our case here demonstrates the application of AHP to a contemporary design problem for a cutting-edge technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
An informative but simple illustration can be extracted
\emph default
.
 The AHP problem was designed to be 
\emph on
hierarchical
\emph default
.
 Complex multi-criterion decision problems often involve dividing and conquering.
 A large AHP application might involve the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nesting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
